meMeanings":[{"name":"Bate","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from the Middle English personal name <i>Bate</i>. It could represent an unrecorded Old English name <i>Bata</i>, or a form of <i>Batte</i>, a short form of Anglo-Norman French names beginning with <i>Bart-</i>, such as <i>Bartelmeu</i> (see   Bartholomew  ) or <i>Bartram</i> (see   Bertram  ).","perhaps a topographic name from an unrecorded Middle English antecedent of the modern English dialect <i>bate</i> ‘river island or land liable to flooding’.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Bateson","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): patronymic from   Bate   or   Batt  ."]},{"name":"Batten","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Baten</i> or <i>Batun</i>, a diminutive of <i>Bat</i> (see   Bate  )."]},{"name":"Batey","meanings":["English (mainly Northumberland): from a pet form of the Middle English personal name <i>Bate</i> (see   Bate  )."]},{"name":"Batkin","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Batkin</i>, from the personal name   Bate   + the diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>."]},{"name":"Bartholomew","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Bertilmew</i>, <i>Bertelmy</i>, a borrowing of the Old French form of the Biblical personal name <i>Bartholomew</i> (from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i>; Hebrew ‘son of Talmai’, said to mean ‘having many furrows’, i.e. rich in land). This was an extremely popular personal name in Christian Europe, with many vernacular derivatives. It derived its popularity from the apostle Saint Bartholomew (Matthew 10:3), who was, among other things, the patron saint of tanners, vintners, and butlers.","As an Irish name, it has been used as an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Pharthaláin</b> (see   McFarlane  )."]},{"name":"Bateman","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Bateman</i>, <i>Bat(te)man</i>, and in the West Midlands of England <i>Batemon</i>, a pet form of   Bate   or   Batte   with the hypocoristic suffix <i>-man</i>."]},{"name":"Bates","meanings":["English: variant of   Bate   with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is also common in Ireland.","Americanized form of German   Betz  . See also   Betts  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Dell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, originally a local name for someone who lived in a <i>dell</i> or hollow."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":24,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":55,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":80,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hung